<h2><a name="chapter1">Chapter 1</a></h2>

<h3><a name="wa-desu"N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ha</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub> <hiragana>desu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
N<sub>1</sub> is the topic of the sentence and is marked by <hiragana>ha</hiragana>. <br/>
N<sub>2</sub> gives more information about the topic. <br/>
<hiragana>desu</hiragana> serves to indicate both assertion and the politeness level. <br/>
<hiragana>desu</hiragana> can inflect to indicate negation, past tense or both.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter2">Chapter 2</a></h2>

<h3><name="kosoado"><hiragana>kosoado</hiragana> demontratives</a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>kore, sore</hiragana> and <hiragana>are</hiragana> are demonstratives and work as nouns.</br>
<hiragana>kore</hiragana> refers to things near to the speaker.</br>
<hiragana>sore</hiragana> refers to things near to the listener.</br>
<hiragana>are</hiragana> refers to things far from both the speaker and the listener.</br>
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> kore ha nann desu ka. </hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> sore ha jisho desu ka.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> kore wo kudasai.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="kono-N"><hiragana>kono</hiragana>N / <hiragana>sono</hiragana>N / <hiragana>ano</hiragana>N</a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>kono, sono</hiragana> and <hiragana>ano</hiragana> are used to modify nouns.
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> kono </hiragana> &#x672c <hiragana> ha </hiragana>
             &#x79c1<hiragana>no desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> ano kata ha donata desu ka.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="sou-desu"><hiragana>sou desu /sou jya arimasenn</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>sou</hiragana> is used to answer a noun sentence in either the affirmative (with <hiragana>sou
desu</hiragana>) or the negative (with <hiragana>sou jya arimasenn</hiragana>). An equivalent negative response
would be to use <hiragana><kanji>chiga</kanji>masu</hiragana>.
</p>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> sore ha <kanji>hon</kanji> desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> hai, sou desu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> &nbsp;</td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> sore ha <kanji>hon</kanji> desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> iie, sou jya arimasenn.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> &nbsp;</td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> sore ha <kanji>hon</kanji> desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> iie, <kanji>chiga</kanji>imasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="ka-ka">S1 <hiragana>ka,</hiragana> S2 <hiragana>ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This form is used to ask a listener to choose between alternatives S<sub>1</sub> and S<sub>2</sub>.
</p>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> kore ha [9] desu ka, [7] desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> [9] desu</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="N1-no-N2">N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>no</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub></a></h3>

<p>
There are several meanings for this construction.
<ol>
<li> N<sub>1</sub> explains what N<sub>2</sub> is about.
<li> N<sub>1</sub> explains who owns N<sub>2</sub>.
</ol>
</p>

<h3><a name="sou-desu-ka"><hiragana>sou desu ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This expression is used to show that the speaker has understood some new information.
</p>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> kono kasa ha anatanodesuka. </hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> iie, chigaimasu. tanakasannnodesu. </hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> sou desu ka. </hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<h2><a name="chapter3">Chapter 3</a></h2>

<h3><a name="kochira"><hiragana>koko/soko/asoko/kochira/sochira/achira</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>koko</hiragana>, <hiragana>soko</hiragana> and <hiragana>asoko</hiragana> refer to a place.</br>
<hiragana>kochira</hiragana>, <hiragana>sochira</hiragana> and <hiragana>achira</hiragana> are demonstratives
that refer to a direction. They can also be used to refer to a place, in which case they are considered more
polite than <hiragana>koko</hiragana>, <hiragana>soko</hiragana> and <hiragana>asoko</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3><a name="doko-dochira"><hiragana>doko/dochira</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>doko</hiragana> means "where" and <hiragana>dochira</hiragana> means "which direction".
<hiragana>dochira</hiragana> can also mean "where", in which case it is more polite than
<hiragana>doko</hiragana>. <br/>
<hiragana>doko</hiragana> or <hiragana>dochira</hiragana> are also used to ask the name of a country, school,
company or any place or organisation to which a person belongs. <hiragana>nann</hiragana> cannot be
used for this purpose.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter4">Chapter 4</a></h2>

<h3><a name="time">Time</a></h3>

The time is expressed using the counters ? and ?. To ask about the time use <hiragana>nann</hiragana> with one of these
 counters.

<h3><a name="masu">V<hiragana>masu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
A verb in the <hiragana>masu</hiragana> form functions as a predicate. It also makes the sentence polite.
</p>

<h3><a name="masen"><hiragana>masu, masenn, mashita, masenn deshita</hiragana></a></h3>

The following forms are used to express various constructs in polite speech.

<table class="example">
  <tr> <th> &nbsp; </th> <th> non-past </th> <th> past </th> </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> affirmative </td>
    <td> ~<hiragana>masu</hiragana> </td>
    <td> ~<hiragana>mashita</hiragana></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> negative </td>
    <td> ~<hiragana>masenn</hiragana> </td>
    <td> ~<hiragana>masenn deshita</hiragana></td>
  </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="time-ni">N<sub>time</sub> <hiragana>ni</hiragana> V</a></h3>

<p>
When a verb denotes a momentary action or movement, the time is marked with the particle <hiragana>ni</hiragana>.
<hiragana>ni</hiragana> is also used when the noun before it uses a numeral. It can also be used with days of the
week but it is often omitted in this case.
</p>

<h3><a name="kara-made">N<sub>1</sub><hiragana>kara</hiragana> N<hiragana>2</hiragana> <hiragana>made</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>kara</hiragana> denotes a starting time or place and <hiragana>made</hiragana> denotes an ending time or place.
They often occur as a pair.
</p>

<h3><a name="n1-to-n2">N<sub>1</sub><hiragana>to</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>to</hiragana> links two (or more) nouns as an exhaustive list and is usually translated as "and".
</p>

<h3><a name="ne">S <hiragana>ne</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>ne</hiragana> is attached to the end of a sentence to add feeling to what the speaker says and shows the speaker expects
the listener to agree. It is often used to confirm or to elicit confirmation.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter5">Chapter 5</a></h2>

<h3><a name="place-he">N<sub>place</sub> <hiragana>he <kanji>i</kanji>kimasu/<kanji>ku</kanji>masu/
<kanji>kae</kanji>rimasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
With a verb of motion, the particle <hiragana>he</hiragana> is put after the place noun to show the direction
of the move.
</p>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kyoto <em>he</em> <kanji>i</kanji>kimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>nihonn <em>he</em> <kanji>ku</kanji>mashita. </hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>uchi <em>he</em> <kanji>kae</kanji>rimasu. </hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="mo-negative">interrogative + <hiragana>mo</hiragana> + negative verb</a></h3>

<p>
When an interrogative is followed by the particle <hiragana>mo</hiragana> and the associated verb is in the
negative, everything represented by the interrogative is denied.
</p>

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>doko he mo <kanji>i</kanji>kimasenn. </hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>nani mo tabemasenn. </hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>dare mo imasenn. </hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="vehicle-de">N<sub>vehicle</sub> <hiragana>de</hiragana> V<sub>motion</motion></a></h3>

<p>
In this sentence pattern, <hiragana>de</hiragana> indicates a means of transportation. <br/>
Note that if you walk somewhere, the expression <hiragana>aruite</hiragana> is used and the particle
<hiragana>de</hiragana> is not used in this case.
</p>

<h3><a name="person-to">N<sub>person</sub><> or N<sub>animal</sub> <hiragana>to</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When an action takes place with a person or animal, that person or animal is marked with the particle <hiragana>to</hiragana>,
which is translated as "with".
</p>

<h3><a name="itsu"><hiragana>itsu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>nann</hiragana> is often used to ask about time, but <hiragana>itsu</hiragana> can also be used to ask when something
will happen or when something happened. <hiragana>itsu</hiragana> does not take the particle <hiragana>ni</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3><a name="yo">S <hiragana>yo</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>yo</hiragana> is used at the end of a sentence to emphasise the information. It can also show that you are expressing
your views assertively.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter6">Chapter 6</a></h2>

<h3><a name="wo-V">N <hiragana>wo</hiragana> V<sub>transitive</sub></a></h3>

<p>
The particle <hiragana>wo</hiragana> is used to mark the object of a transitive verb. Note that a verb that is transitive in
English is not necessarily transitive in japanese, and vice-versa.

</p>

<h3><a name="wo-shimasu">N <hiragana>wo shimasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This construction is used to create new verbs: the action denoted by the noun is performed.
</p>

<h3><a name="nani-wo"><hiragana>nani wo shimasu ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This expression is used to ask what someone will do. If <hiragana>shimasu</hiragana> is changed to <hiragana>shimashita</hiragana>
then the expression is asking what someone has already done.
</p>

<h3><a name="nani-vs-nan"><hiragana>nani</hiragana> and <hiragana>nann</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>nann</hiragana> is used:
<ol>
<li> before a word whose first mora is in the <hiragana>ta</hiragana>, <hiragana>da</hiragana> or <hiragana>na</hiragana>
row.
<li> when it is followed by a counter suffix or similar
</ol>

In all other cases <hiragana>nani</hiragana> is used. Note that the kanji is always the same.
</p>

<h3><a name="place-de">N<sub>place</sub> <hiragana>de</hiragana> V</a></h3>

<p>
When <hiragana>de</hiragana> follows a noun denoting a place, the noun is the place where an action occurs.
</p>

<h3><a name="masen-ka">V <hiragana>masen ka</hiragana><a/></h3>

<p>
If you wish to invite a listener to do something.
</p>

<h3><a name="mashou-ka">V <hiragana>mashou ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This expression is used to invite a listener positively to do something. It is also used when responfding positively to an
invitation. Note that an invitation using <hiragana>masen ka</hiragana> shows more consideration for the listener (because it
anticipates a possible negative reply) and so is considered more polite.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter7">Chapter 7</a></h2>

<h3><a name="tool-de">N<sub>tool/means</sub> <hiragana>de</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
The particle <hiragana>de</hiragana> indicates a method or a means used for an action.
</p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> hashi de tabemasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> nihongo de repo-to wo kakimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="word-sentence">Word Sentence</a></h3>

<p>
To ask how to say a word in an other language use this sentence pattern:
</p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>[arigatou] ha eigo de nann desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>[</hiragana>Thank you<hiragana>] desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="ni-agemasu">N<sub>person</sub> <hiragana>ni agemasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
Verbs such as <hiragana>agemasu</hiragana>, <hiragana>kashimasu</hiragana> and <hiragana>oshiemasu</hiragana> mark the
person to whom something is given, lent or taught with <hiragana>ni</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3><a name="ni-moraimasu">N<sub>person</sub> <hiragana>ni moraimasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
Verbs such as <hiragana>moraimasu</hiragana>, <hiragana>karimasu</hiragana> and <hiragana>naraimasu</hiragana> express
actions from the point of view of the receiver. With these verbs the agent from whom the action is received is marked
with the particle <hiragana>ni</hiragana>.
</p>

<p>
<hiragana>kara</hiragana> is sometimes used instead of <hiragana>ni</hiragana>. When the agent is an organisation such as
a school or a company, <hiragana>kara</hiragana> must be used.
</p>

<h3><a name="mou-V"><hiragana>mou</hiragana> V <hiragana>mashita</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>mou</hiragana> means already and is used with V<hiragana>mashita</hiragana> to indicate that an action has
been completed.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter8">Chapter 8</a></h2>

<h3><a name="adjectives">adjectives</a></h3>

<p>
See <a name="adjectives.html"> the adjectives page</a> for further information.
</p>

<h3><a name="totemo"><hiragana>totemo, amari</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>totemo</hiragana> and <hiragana>amari</hiragana> are adverbs of degree. They immediately precede the 
adjectives they modify.
<br/>
<hiragana>totemo</hiragana> means "very" and is used in affirmative sentences.<br/>
<hiragana>amari</hiragana> means "not very" and is used in negative sentences.
</p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <katakana>pekinn</katakana> <hiragana>ha <em>totemo</em>
	<kanji>samui</kanji>ii desu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td> Beijing is very cold.</td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> kore ha <em>totemo</em> <kanji>arinashi namae</kanji>na
	<kanji>utsuru yonkaku</kanji> desu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td> This is a very famous film.</td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <katakana>shyannhai</katakana> <hiragana>ha <em>amari</em> <kanji>samui</kanji>kunai desu.
</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td> Shanghai is not very cold.</td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>sakura<kanji>ookii manabu</kanji> ha <em>amari</em>
  <kanji>arinashi namae</kanji>na <kanji>ookii manabu</kanji>jya arimasen.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td> </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="dou-desu-ka">N <hiragana>ha dou desu ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This question is used to ask for the listener's impression about a place or a thing.
</p>

<h3><a name="donna">N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>donnna</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub> <hiragana>desu ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used when the speaker wants the listener to describe or explain N<sub>1</sub>.
N<sub>2</sub> is a category to which N<sub>1</sub> belongs.
</p>

<h3><a name="S-ga-S">S<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ga,</hiragana> S<sub>2</sub></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>ga</hiragana> is a particle used to link sentences and in this usage means "but".
</p>

<h3><a name="dore"><hiragana>dore</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>dore</hiragana> is an interrogative used to ask the listener to choose one item from a
set of <em>three</em> or more things.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter9">Chapter 9</a></h2>

<h3><a name="donna-N"><hiragana>donna</hiragana> N</a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>donna</hiragana> is used to ask the listener to name one of a group which N describes.
</p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>donna<katakana>supotsu</katakana> ga suki desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana><katakana>sakka-</katakana> ga suki desu.</hiragana>.</td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="daitai"><hiragana>yoku, daitai</hiragana> etc.</a></h3>

<p>
These adverbs are placed before verbs to modify them.
</p>

<table>
<tr> <th>degree</th> <th> adverb + affirmative </th> <th> adverb + negative </th> </tr>
<tr> <td> high   </td> <td> <hiragana>yoku wakarimasu</hiragana> </td> <td> &nbsp; </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> &nbsp; </td> <td> <hiragana>daitai wakarimasu</hiragana> </td> <td> &nbsp; </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> low    </td> <td> <hiragana>sukoshi wakarimasu</hiragana> </td> <td> amari wakarimasenn </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> &nbsp; </td> <td> &nbsp;</td> <td> zennzenn wakarimasenn </td> </tr>
</table>

<table>
<tr> <th>amount</th> <th> adverb + affirmative </th> <th> adverb + negative </th> </tr>
<tr> <td> large  </td> <td> <hiragana>takusann arimasu</hiragana> </td> <td> &nbsp; </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> small  </td> <td> <hiragana>sukoshi  arimasu</hiragana> </td> <td> amari arimasenn </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> &nbsp; </td> <td> &nbsp; </td> <td> zennzenn arimasenn </td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="S-kara">S<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>kara,</hiragana> S<sub>2</sub></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>kara</hiragana> connects to sentences and indicates a causal relationship, S<sub>1</sub> is the
reason for S<sub>2</sub>.
</p>

<h3><a name="doushite"><hiragana>doushite</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>doushite</hiragana> is used to ask a reason for something. The reply should end in <hiragana>kara</hiragana>.
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>doushite asa shinnbunn yomimasenn ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>jikann ga arimasenn kara.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<h2><a name="chapter10">Chapter 10</a></h2>

<h3><a name="existence">Existence: N ga <hiragana>arimasu/imasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to indicate the existence or presence of a thing or a person. The thing or person
is treated as the subject and marked with the particle <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.<br/>
<hiragana>aru</hiragana> is used for inanimate or non-moving items; plants fall into this category.<br/>
<hiragana>iru</hiragana> is used for animate items, for example people and animals.
</p>

<h3><a name="exist-place">N<sub>place</sub> <hiragana>ni</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub>
<hiragana>ga arimasu/imasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to inidcate that N<sub>2</sub> is present at location N<sub>1</sub>.
</p>

<h3><a name="exist-topic">N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ha</hiragana> N<sub>place</sub>
<hiragana>ni arimasu/imasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to inidcate that N<sub>1</sub> is present at location N<sub>place</sub>.
</p>

<h3><a name="thing-no-place">N<sub>place,person,thing</sub><hiragana>no</hiragana>N<sub>position</sub></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to indicate where an item is relative to another noun.<br/>
Some nouns denoting position are:
<hiragana>
<ol>
<li> ue
<li> shita
<li> mae
<li> ushiro
<li> migi
<li> hidari
<li> naka
<li> soto
<li> tonari
<li> chikaku
<li> aida
</ol>
</hiragana>
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>tsukue ue ni shashinn ga arimasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>yuubinnkyoku ha ginnkou no tonari arimasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>eki no chikaku de tomodachi ni aimasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<p>
Note that as these are place nouns they can sometimes take the particle <hiragana>de</hiragana>, as shown
in the third example sentence.
</p>


<h3><a name="ya">N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ya</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>ya</hiragana> is used to link nouns in a non-exhaustive list. This is in contrast to
<hiragana>to</hiragana> which links nouns in an exhaustive list. Sometimes the last noun is followed by
<hiragana>nado</hiragana> to explictly indicate that there some other items not enumerated in the list.
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>hako no naka ni tegami ya shashinn ga arimasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>hako no naka ni tegami ya shashinn nado ga arimasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="desu-ka">Word(s) <hiragana>desu ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>ka</hiragana> can be used to confirm using this pattern.
</p>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>sumimasenn. <katakana>yunyu-ya sutoa</katakana> ha doko desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana><katakana>yunyu-ya sutoa</katakana> desu ka. ano
  <katakana>bitu</katakana> no nako desu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>

<h3><a name="arimasen-ka"><hiragana>arimasenn ka</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
By using the negative form <hiragana>arimasenn ka</hiragana> the speaker is being polite by preparing for a 
possible negative answer.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter11">Chapter 11</a></h2>

<h3><a name="numbers">Numbers</a></h3>

<p>
These words are used to count the numbers from 1 to 10.
<table>
<tr> <td> 1  </td> <td><hiragana>hitotsu</hiragana></td>   <td> <kanji>ichi</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 2  </td> <td><hiragana>futatsu</hiragana></td>   <td> <kanji>ni</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 3  </td> <td><hiragana>mittsu</hiragana></td>    <td> <kanji>san</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 4  </td> <td><hiragana>yottsu</hiragana></td>    <td> <kanji>yon</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 5  </td> <td><hiragana>itsutsu</hiragana></td>   <td> <kanji>go</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 6  </td> <td><hiragana>muttsu</hiragana></td>    <td> <kanji>roku</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 7  </td> <td><hiragana>nanatsu</hiragana></td>   <td> <kanji>nana</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 8  </td> <td><hiragana>yattsu</hiragana></td>    <td> <kanji>hachi</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 9  </td> <td><hiragana>kokonotsu</hiragana></td> <td> <kanji>kyuu</kanji><hiragana>tsu</hiragana> </td></tr>
<tr> <td> 10 </td> <td><hiragana>too</hiragana></td>       <td> 10 </td></tr>
</table>

Elevent and higher are counted using the numbers themselves.
</p>

<h3><a name="counters">Counters</a></h3>

<p>
Counter suffixes are used when counting some sorts of things or expressing quantities.

<table>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>ninn</hiragana> </td> <td> number of people </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>dai</hiragana> </td> <td> number of machines or vehicles </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>mai</hiragana> </td> <td> number of thin or flat things </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>kai</hiragana> </td> <td> times</td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>funn</hiragana> </td> <td> minutes  </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>jikann</hiragana> </td> <td> hours  </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>nichi</hiragana> </td> <td> days  </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>shuukann</hiragana> </td> <td> weeks  </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>ka getsu</hiragana> </td> <td> months  </td> </tr>
<tr> <td> <hiragana>nenn</hiragana> </td> <td> years  </td> </tr>
</table>

Counters usually follow the noun and particle to which they apply. However, with lengths of time this is not
always the case.
</p>

<h3><a name="interrogatives">Interrogatives</a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>ikutsu</hiragana> is used to as "how many" for those things counted with the general counter 
<hiragana>hitotsu</hiragana>, <hiragana>futotsu</hiragana>.<br/>
<hiragana>nann</hiragana> is used with a counter suffix to ask "how many".<br/>
<hiragana>donogurai</hiragana> is used to ask how long something takes.<br/>
<hiragana>gurai</hiragana> is added after a quantifier to mean "about".
</p>

<h3><a name="#kai">Quantifier<sub>period</sub> <hiragana>ni ichi kai</hiragana> V</a></h3>

<p>
With this expression you can say how often you do something.
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>1ka getsu ni 2kai eiga wo mimasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="dake">Quantifier <hiragana>dake</hiragana>/N <hiragana>dake</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>dake</hiragana> means "only". It is added after quantifiers or nouns to express
that there is no more or nothing else.
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana><katakana>pawa-</katakana>denki ni gaigokujinn no shain ga
	hitotsu dake imasu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>yasumi ha nichiyoubi dake desu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter12">Chapter 12</a></h2>

<h3><a name="#na-adj-past">Past Tense of Noun and na-adjective Sentences</a></h3>

<p>
See the <a href="adjectives.html">adjectives</a> page.
</p>

<h3><a name="i-adj-past">Past Tense of <hiragana>i</hiragana>-adjective Sentences</a></h3>

<p>
See the <a href="adjectives.html">adjectives</a> page.
</p>

<h3><a name="yori-adj">N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ha</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub> <hiragana>yori</hiragana> adjective 
<hiragana>desu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern describes the quality or state of N<sub>1</sub> in comparison to N<sub>2</sub>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kono kuruma ha ano kuruma <em>yori</em> <kanji>ookii</kanji>kii desu.</hiragana></td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="no-hou-ga">N<sub>1</sub><hiragana>to</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub><hiragana>to
  dochira ga</hiragana> adjective <hiragana>desu ka.</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
The question asks the listener to choose between two items; the interrogative <hiragana>dochira</hiragana> is used
since two items are invovled.
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana><katakana>sakka-</katakana> to yakyuu to <em>dochira</em> ga omoshiroi 
	desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana><katakana>sakka-</katakana> <em>no hou ga</em> omoshiroi desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="ichiban">N <hiragana>no naka de</hiragana> interrogative <hiragana> ga ichibann</hiragana>
 adjective <hiragana>desu ka.</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to ask the listener to select the "best". The interrogative used depends on the category
and may be one of <hiragana>nani</hiragana>, <hiragana>doko</hiragana>, <hiragana>dare</hiragana> and
<hiragana>itsu</hiragana>.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>nihonn ryouri no naka de nani ga ichibann oishii desu ka.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>tennpura ga ichibann oishii desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td><katakana>E-roppa</katakana> <hiragana>de doko ga ichibann yokatta desu ka.</hiragana></td></tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td><katakana>suisu</katakana> <hiragana>ga ichibann yokatta desu.</hiragana></td></tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter13">Chapter 13</a></h2>

<h3><a name="hoshii">N <hiragana>ga hoshii desu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to express the speaker's desire to possess an object. It can also be used
to ask about what the speaker wants. The object is marked with the particle <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.

<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td><kanji>watashi</kanji> <hiragana>ha tomodachi ga hoshii desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>ima nani ga ichibann hoshii desu ka.</hiragana></td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>kuruma ga hoshii desu.</hiragana></td></tr>
</table>

</p>

<h3><a name="tai-desu"> -tai desu</a></h3>

<p>
The suffix <hiragana>tai</hiragana> is attached to the <hiragana>masu</hiragana> stem of a verb to form
an expression that expresses the speaker's desire to do something. The particle <hiragana>wo</hiragana> may
be replaced by the particle <hiragana>ga</hiragana> (other particles are not replaced). The <hiragana>tai
</hiragana> for conjugates as an <hiragana>i</hiragana> adjective.

<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td><kanji>watashi</kanji> <hiragana>ha okinawa he ikitai desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td><kanji>watashi</kanji> <hiragana>ha tennpura ga tabetai desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>onaka ga itai desu kara, nanimo tabetakunai desu.</hiragana> </td></tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="purpose"> N<sub>place</sub> <hiragana>he</hiragana> V-<hiragana>masu ni</hiragana> 
    V<sub>motion</sub></a></h3>

<p>
The purpose for the movement is expressed in this sentence pattern.

<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>kobe he <katakana>inndo</katakana> ryouri wo <em>tabe</em> ni ikimasu.</hiragana>
    </td></tr>
</table>

</p>

<h3><a name="goal">N <hiragana>ni</hiragana> V/N <hiragana>wo</hiragana> V</a></h3>

<p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <tr> <td><hiragana>7ji ni uchi wo demasu.</hiragana></td></tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="dokoka"><hiragana>dokoka/nanika</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>dokoka</hiragana> means "anywhere" or "somewhere".<br/>
<hiragana>nanika</hiragana> means "anything" or "something".<br/>

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>fuyuyasumi ha dokoka he ikimashita ka.</hiragana></td></tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>hai, ikimashita.</hiragana></td></tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td><hiragana>nodo ga kawakimashita kara, nanika wo nomitaidesu.</hiragana></td></tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter14">Chapter 14</a></h2>

<h3>Verb Conjugation and Verb Groups</h3>

<p>
Japanese verbs are split into 3 categories:
<ol>
<li> <hiragana>godann</hiragana> verbs
<li> <hiragana>ichidann</hiragana> verbs
<li> irregular verbs (<hiragana>suru</hiragana> and <hiragana>kuru</hiragana>)
</ol>
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form</h3>

<p>
The formation of the -<hiragana>te</hiragana> form of a verb is described elsewhere.
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form <hiragana>kudasai</hiragana></h3>

<p>
In this sentence pattern the speaker encourages or asks the listener to perform some action.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>sumimasenn, kono kanji no yomikata wo oshiete kudasai.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana> koko ni jyuusho to namae wo kiite kudasai.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form <hiragana>imasu</hiragana></h3>

<p>
The form -<hiragana>te imasu</hiragana> is used to indicate that an action or state is ongoing.
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form <hiragana>mashou ka</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to frame a question of the form "Shall I ...".
</p>

<h3>S<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ga,</hiragana> S<sub>2</sub></h3>

<p>
In this sentence pattern, <hiragana>ga</hiragana> is used to lightly connect S<sub>1</sub> to S<sub>2</sub>.
</p>

<h3>N <hiragana>ga</hiragana> V</h3>

<p>
When describing a natural phenomenon, the subject is indicated by <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>ame ga futte imasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter15">Chapter 15</a></h2>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form <hiragana>mou ii desu</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to grant permission.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>shashinn wo totte mo ii desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
With the addition of <hiragana>ka</hiragana>, this becomes a request for permission.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> tabako wo sutte mo ii desu ka.</td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form <hiragana>ha ikemasenn</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to express prohibition ("must not do").
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form <hiragana>imasu</hiragana></h3>

<p>
In addition to other uses, this sentence pattern is used to describe a state that continues in the present
which results from an action in the past.
</p>

<p>
A further use of this form is to express a habitual action, that is, the same action performed repeatedly
over a period of time.
</P>

<h3><hiragana>shirimasenn</hiragana></h3>

<p>
The negative form of <hiragana>shitte</hiragana> is <hiragana>shirimasenn</hiragana>. That is, knowing something
is expressed with the -<hiragana>te</hiragana> form but not knowing is expressed with the non-past negative.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter16">Chapter 16</a></h2>

<h3>Connecting Verb Sentences with -<hiragana>te</hiragana> form</h3>

<p>
A further use of the -<hiragana>te</hiragana> form is to connect together two or more actions that happen
in succession. The tense of the sentence as a whole is determined by the tense of the final verb.
</p>

<h3>Joining <hiragana>i</hiragana>-adjectives</h3>

<p>
To join an <hiragana>i</hiragana>-adjective to a subsequent sentence, remove the <hiragana>i</hiragana> and
add <hiragana>kute</hiragana>.

<h3>Joining N or <hiragana>na</hiragana>-adjectives</h3>

<p>
When joining a noun N or a <hiragana>na</hiragana>-adjective to a subsequent sentence, remove the final
<hiragana>desu</hiragana> and replace it with <hiragana>de</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3>V<sub>1</sub>-<hiragana>te kara,</hiragana> V<sub>2</sub2></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern states that once V<sub>1</sub> has happened, V<sub>2</sub> will happen. The tense of the whole sentence
is determined by the tense of the final verb.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <katakana>konsa-to</katakana><hiragana>ga owatte kara, <katakana>resutorann</katakana>
      de shokuji shimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>N<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>ha</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub> <hiragana>ga</hiragana> adjective</h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to describe an attribute of a thing or a person.
N<sub>1</sub> is the topic.
N<sub>2</sub> is the subject of the adjective's description.
</p>

<h3><hiragana>douyatte</hiragana></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>douyatte</hiragana> is used to ask how to do something.
</p>

<h3><hiragana>dono</hiragana> N</h3>

<p>
<hiragana>dono</hiragana> is used to ask the listener to define one item among three or more that are present.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter17">Chapter 17</a></h2>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>nai</hiragana> form</h3>

<p>
The V-<hiragana>nai</hiragana> form is also known as the V<sub>1</sub> base.
</p>

<h3>V<sub>1</sub><hiragana>naide kudasai</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This form is used to instruct or to ask the listener not to do something.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>koko ni shashinn wo toranaide kudasai.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>V<sub>1</sub><hiragana>nakereba narimasen</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern indicates that something <em>must</em> be done irrespective of the will
of the actor. There is no negative meaning associated with this expression.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kusuri wo nominakereba narimasenn.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
</p>

<h3>V<sub>1</sub><hiragana>nakute mo ii desu</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence indicates that the action described by the verb does not have to be done.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>ashita konakutemo ii desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="en"> <td> You don't have to come tomorrow.</td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>N<sub>object</sub><hiragana>ha</hiragana></h3>

<p>
The particle <hiragana>wo</hiragana> marking a direct object can be replaced with
<hiragana>ha</hiragana> if the object is to be made a topic.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>koko ni nimotsu wo okanaide kudasai.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>nimotsu ha koko ni okanaide kudasai.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>N<sub>time</sub><hiragana>made ni</hiragana> V</h3>

<p>
The point in time marked by <hiragana>madeni</hiragana> is the time limit by which
an action is to be completed.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kaigi ha 5ji madeni owarimasu</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>doyoubi madeni honn wo kaesanakereba narimasenn.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
<h2><a name="chapter18">Chapter 18</a></h2>

<h3>Verb Dictionary Form</h3>

<p>
This is the basic form of a verb and is the form in which it will be found in a dictionary. All other forms should
be regarded as derived from this form (rather than from the <hiragana>masu</hiragana> form).
</p>

<h3><hiragana>dekiru</hiragana></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>dekiru</hiragana> is the verb which expresses ability or possibility.
The pattern N <hiragana>ga dekiru</hiragana> indicates that which is possible. N may be replaced by
V<sub>3</sub> <hiragana>koto</hiragana>.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <katakana>mira-</katakana><hiragana>sann ha nihongo ga dekimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kotoshi ha <katakana>suki-</katakana>ga dekimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <katakana>ka-do</katakana><hiragana>de harau koto ga dekimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3Hobbies</h3>

<p>
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>watashi no shumi ha ongaku desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>watashi no shumi ha ongaku wo kiku koto desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3>V<sub>1</sub> <hiragana>mae ni,</hiragana> V<sub>2</sub></h3>

<p>
This pattern indicates that V<sub>2</sub> occurs before V<sub>1</sub> happens.
V<sub>1</sub> may be replaced by N<hiragana>no</hiragana> or by a quantifier specifying time.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>nihonn he kuru mae ni, nihongo wo benkyou shimashita.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>shokuji no mae ni, te wo araimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>tanakasann ha 1jikann mae ni, dekakemashita.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><hiragana>nakanaka</hiragana></h3>

<p>
When accompaned by a negative expression, this means "not easily" or "not as expected".
</p>

<h3><hiragana>zehi</hiragana></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>zehi</hiragana> is used with expressions of hope and request and emphasises the meaning of the expression.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter19">Chapter 19</a></h2>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>ta</hiragana>-form</h3>

<p>
The <hiragana>ta</hiragana>-form is derived in the same was as the <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form
except that <hiragana>te</hiragana> is replaced by <hiragana>ta</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3>Verb <hiragana>ta</hiragana>-form <hiragana>kotoga arimasu</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to describe an experience that one has already had. It indicates that something
has been experienced in the past and is subtly different to a sentence stating that an action was performed
at a specific point in the past.
</p>

<h3>V <hiragana>ta ri,</hiragana> V <hiragana>ta ri suru</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern indicates that a number of actions amongst many actions are performed. The tense of
the sentence depends on the tense of the final verb. It is often translated by "and so on". It differs from
the use of the <hiragana>te</hiragana>-form in that there is no implied temporal sequence in the verbs.
</p>

<h3><hiragana>narimasu</hiragana></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>narimasu</hiragana> is appended to an adverb to indicate a change in a state or a condition.
</p>

<h3><hiragana>sou desu ne</hiragana></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>sou desu ne</hiragana> is used to agree with the speaker or to sympathise with the speaker.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter20">Chapter 20</a></h2>

<h3><a name="polite-vs-plain">Polite vs Plain Style</a></h3>

<p>
Japanese language is either in polite style or plain style. The former is characterised by a sentence-final copula in 
<hiragana>desu</hiragana> form or a sentence-final verb in <hiragana>masu</hiragana> form.

<h3><a name="polite-plain-use">Proper Use of Polite and Plain Style</a></h3>

<p>
Polite style is used for:
<ol>
<li> Daily communication between adults who are not close friends.
<li> Most letters.
</ol>

The plain style is used for:
<ol>
<li> Talking with one's close friends, colleagues and family members.
<li> Written works such as newspapers, diaries and books.
</ol>
</p>

<h3><a name="plain-conversation">Conversation in Plain Style</a></h3>

<p>
Conversations in plain style have a number of characteristics.
<ol>
<li> Questions generally omit <hiragana>ka</hiragana> and use a rising intonation at the end of the sentence instead.
<li> In noun and <hiragana>na</hiragana>-adjective replies <hiragana>da</hiragana> is usually omitted.
<li> Certain particles are omitted if the meaning of the sentence is still clear from the context.
<li> V<hiragana>te iru</hiragana> often becomes V<hiragana>te ru</hiragana> (i.e. the <hiragana>i</hiragana> is dropped.
<li> <hiragana>kedo</hiragana> is often used in place of the connective <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.
</ol>

</p>

<h2><a name="chapter21">Chapter 21</a></h2>

<h3><a name="to-omoimasu"><hiragana>to moimasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This construct is used after an expression in the plain form to:
<ol>
<li> express conjecture
<li> express an opinion
</ol>
</p>

<h3><a name="to-iimasu"><hiragana>to iimasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern may be used in two ways.
<ol>
<li> To directly quote what someone says or has said, repeat their words exactly and follow with <hiragana>to iimasu</hiragana>.
<li> To quote indirectly, use the plain form before <hiragana>to iimasu</hiragana>. The tense of the quoted text is 
unaffected by the tense of the main sentence.
</ol>
</p>

<h3><a name="deshou"><hiragana>deshou</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When the speaker expects the listener to have some knowledge of the topic at hand and believes that the
listener will agree with the speaker's view, <hiragana>deshou</hiragana> is used with a rising intonation
to confirm the listener's agreement.
</p>

<h3><a name="to-be-held">N<sub>place</sub><hiragana> de</hiragana> N<sub>2</sub> <hiragana>ga arimasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When N<sub>2</sub> is an event or a partyy etc., <hiragana>arimasu</hiragana> means "to be held" and N<sub>place</sub>
is where the event will happen.
</p>

<h3><a name="occasion">N<occasion> <hiragana>de</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When an action happens on a certain occasion, the occasion is marked by <hiragana>de</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3><a name="N-de-mo">N <hiragana>de mo</hiragana> V</a></h3>

<p>
When making a suggestion or advising, <hiragana>de mo</hiragana> is used to give an example of the
class of things that could be done.
</p>

<h3><a name="nai-to">V-<hiragana>nai to</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This form is used to express the construct "have to".
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter22">Chapter 22</a></h2>

<h3><a name="noun-modification">Noun Modification</a></h3>

<p>
Anything that modifies a noun <em>always</em> precedes that noun.
</p>

<h3><a name="noun-modification-by-sentence">Noun Modification by Sentences</a></h3>

<p>
<ol>
<li> The predicate of the sentence which modifies a noun is in the plain form.
<li> The noun modified by a sentence can be used in various parts of a new sentence.
</ol>
</p>
<h3><a name="N-ga-in-modifiers">N <hiragana>ga</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When a sentence modifies a noun, the subject in that sentence is indicated by <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3><a name="time-for-doing">V-dictionary <hiragana>jikann/yakusoku/youji</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When expressing the time for doing some activity, put the dictionary form of the action before
<hiragana>jikann</hiragana>.
</p>

<h2><a name="chapter23">Chapter 23</a></h2>

<h3><a name="toki"><hiragana>toki</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>toki</hiragana> is used to link two sentences and expresses the time when the action described in the
main sentence occurs.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>toshokann de kariru toki, <katakana>ka-do</katakana>ga irimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>tsuma ga byouki no toki, kaisha wo yasumimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="toki-V"><hiragana>toki</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When a dictionary form of a predicate is followed by <hiragana>toki</hiragana>, it indicates that the action has not been
completed; when the <hiragana>ta</hiragana>-form is used, it indicates that the action has been completed.
</p>

<p>
Consider these two sentences:
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kuni he kaeru toki, kabann wo kaimashita.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kuni he kaetta toki, kabann wo kaimashita.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
In the first sentence, the speaker has not yet reached his destination and that the bag was purchased sometime during the trip.
In the second sentence, the speaker bought a bag after arriving at the destination.
</p>

<h3><a name="inevitable-to">V<sub>dictionary</sub> <hiragana>to</hiragana></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used when expressing the idea that a consequence is an inevitable outcome
of a specified action.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>kono <katakana>botann</katakana>osu to, otsuri ga demasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="ga-scene">N <hiragana>ga</hiragana> adjective/V</a></h3>

<p>
When describing a state or a scene, the subject is indicated by <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.
</p>

<h3><a name="wo-passing">N<sub>place</sub> <hiragana>wo</hiragana> V<sub>movement</sub></a></h3>

<p>
The particle <hiragana>wo</hiragana> is used with a verb of movement to indicate the place where a person
or thing passes.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>koenn wo sannposhimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>

</p>

<h2><a name="chapter24">Chapter 24</a></h2>

<h3><a name="kuremasu"><hiragana>kuremasu</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>ageru</hiragana> is used when the speaker gives something to someone else. Hwoever, when the speaker,
or a member of his family etc., is given something, the verb <hiragana>kureru</hiragana> is used instead.
</p>

<h3><a name="te-giving">V-<hiragana>te</hiragana> ... (giving)</a></h3>

<p>
<ol>
<li> V-<hiragana>te ageru</hiragana> indicates that someone does something for someone else with a sense of goodwill.
<li> V-<hiragana>te morau</hiragana> indicates that the speaker receives something with a sense of gratitude.
<li> V-<hiragana>te kureru</hiragana> indicates that the speaker receives something with a sense of gratitude.
</ol>
</p>

<h3>N<sub>person</sub> <hiragana>ga</hiragana> V</h3>

<p>
In reply to a statement or question, the converstaional partner offers new information.
</p>


<h3>Interrogative <hiragana>ga</hiragana> V</h3>

<h2><a name="chapter25">Chapter 25</a></h2>

<h3><a name="past-ra">Plain past <hiragana>ra</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
When <hiragana>ra</hiragana> is attached to the plain past form of a verb, adjective etc., the preceding clause is
changed into a conditional expression. This pattern is used by the speaker to state an opinion, situation, request etc.
</p>

<h3><a name="V-ta-ra">V-<hiragana>ta ra</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This pattern is used to express that an action will be performed once another action, which is certain to happen in
the future, has been completed.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>10jini nattara, dekakemashou.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h3><a name="V-te-mo">V-<hiragana>te mo</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to express a reverse condition. It is used when something which was expected
to happen does not materialise.
</p>

<h3><a name="moshi-ikura"><hiragana>moshi</hiragana> and <hiragana>ikura</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
<hiragana>moshi</hiragana> is used in a sentence in the plain past form to indicate that the sentence will present
a condition.
<hiragana>ikura</hiragana> is used with -<hiragana>te mo</hiragana> to do the same.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>moshi 1okuenn attara, iroiro na kuni wo ryokou shitai desu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>ikura kangaetemo, wakarimasenn.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
</p>

<h3><a name="subordinate-ga">N <hiragana>ga</hiragana></a></h3>

<p>
In subordinate clauses using <hiragana>tara</hiragana>, <hiragana>temo</hiragana>, <hiragana>toki</hiragana>,
<hiragana>to</hiragana>, <hiragana>maeni</hiragana> etc., in addition to <hiragana>kara</hiragana>, the subject
is marked by <hiragana>ga</hiragana>.
<table class="sentence">
<tr class="jp"> <td> <hiragana>tomodachi ga kuru maeni, heya wo souji shimasu.</hiragana> </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

